@nikipore Perhaps the cleanest solution (and easiest) right now is to store the certfile and keyfile parameters on the `StompConfig` instance; and then use them inside `endpointFactory` to build the string.  This way we can avoid having new params being passed through all the functions, although it does mean we'll have to pass the `StompConfig` instance through (or make it available some other way).

The best solution will be to properly design the Twisted client interface using, as @ktdreyer describes, `SSL4ClientEndpoint` (or even simply [Reactor.connectSSL](https://twistedmatrix.com/documents/17.1.0/api/twisted.internet.interfaces.IReactorSSL.connectSSL.html)).  The trick is going to be that we'd have to create our own `sslContextFactory`, which is needed to pass into `SSL4ClientEndpoint`, see [here](https://twistedmatrix.com/documents/17.1.0/api/twisted.internet.endpoints.SSL4ClientEndpoint.html).  The factory needs to return a new [OpenSSL.SSL.Context](https://pyopenssl.readthedocs.io/en/stable/api/ssl.html#OpenSSL.SSL.Context) instance (unfortunately, it looks like Twisted doesn't use the sslContext class from the stdlib, which is what we're using for the sync case).  Such instances, i.e., `OpenSSL.SSL.Context`, need to have [this set of methods](https://pyopenssl.org/en/stable/api/ssl.html#context-objects) configured, and this is where we would do the customization to make sure the certfile and keyfile are available.

