I have the following workaround:

``Products.PluggableAuthservice`` chooses challenges in the following way:``
        for challenger_id, challenger in challengers:
            challenger_protocol = getattr(challenger, 'protocol',
                                          challenger_id)
            if valid_protocols and challenger_protocol not in valid_protocols:
                # Skip invalid protocol for this request type.
                continue
            if protocol is None or protocol == challenger_protocol:
                if challenger.challenge(request, response):
                    protocol = challenger_protocol

        if protocol is not None:
            # something fired, so it was a successful PAS challenge
            return True
``

This means that we can implement the "reject already authenticated user" logic by a special challenge plugin. We must ensure that it comes before the "normal" plugin and that it has an associated "protocol" different from that of the "normal" plugin -- this will inhibit the "normal" plugin once our special challengs has fired. If "protocol chooser" plugins are registered,  one of them must allow our special plugin.

Let's forget about pygit2. Try this code:

```c
#include <git2.h>
#include <git2/sys/transport.h>
#include <stdio.h>

void main()
{
  git_transport *transport;

  int err = git_transport_new(&transport, NULL, "ssh://github.com/libgit2/pygit2.git");
  printf("%d\n", err);
}
```

Call it with:

```sh
gcc test_789.c -lgit2 && ./a.out
```

If it worked you should see a **0**, if it does not you will see a **-1**.

Then to debug I would go for a simple process of edit, build, run. Where editing would be very much about inserting ``printf``. Since there's only one place where this error message is raised, it should not take long.

In the branch ``origin/maint/v0.27`` the file ``src/transport.c`` the line 126 is where that error message is raised:

```c
    if ((error = transport_find_fn(&fn, url, &param)) == GIT_ENOTFOUND) {
        giterr_set(GITERR_NET, "unsupported URL protocol");
        return -1;
```

So ``transport_find_fn`` is returning ``GIT_ENOTFOUND``. That function is just above, line 72. Since you're using Linux that function is rather simple, just a couple of calls to ``transport_find_by_url``.

Apparently ``transport_find_by_url`` is returning ``NULL`` for a ``ssh://`` URL. I would start inserting the ``printf`` there. The loop at line 61, for example:

```c
    /* Find a system transport for this URI */
    for (i = 0; i < GIT_TRANSPORT_COUNT; ++i) {
        d = &transports[i];
        printf("%d: %s\n", i, d->prefix); // <== for example
        if (strncasecmp(url, d->prefix, strlen(d->prefix)) == 0) {
            return d;
        }
    }
```

